body_text.text:
The transmission mode of an infectious disease is the means by which transfer of the infectious agent goes from the source (e.g., a vertebrate donor host) to a susceptible host (recipient), including all contributing factors. This transfer can be either direct or indirect contact, the latter mediated by contaminated excrement, food, animal products, arthropods, etc. Epidemiologists classify the transmission modes (Fig. 5.1) into four categories, as:
contact (direct transmission: contact diseases, including perinatal infections);
inhalation (via air, aerogenically: generally the group of respiratory, air-borne infectious diseases);
ingestion (food-borne and water-borne alimentary, gastrointestinal diseases);
inoculation (group of infections transmissible by haematophagous arthropods, and some nosocomial – acquired in hospital – or iatrogenic infections, i.e., acquired inadvertently during diverse medical procedures and treatments such as injections, infusions, blood transfusions or operations).
